The contributors discuss a wide range of major figures in the long Romantic period, from Kant and Hegel to Nietzsche, as well as key figures defining the contemporary intellectual debate, including Freud, Heidegger, Adorno, Lyotard, Derrida, de Man, and Deleuze and Guattari. While preserving the significance of the historical period extending from Kant to the early nineteenth century, the volume gives the concept of Romantic culture a new historical and philosophical meaning that extends from its pre-Kantian past to our own culture and beyond.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aAbsolute, ThexHistory. 0aIdealism, German. 0aRomanticismzGermany. 4aLiterature : Comparative Literature. 4aLiterature : Romanticism. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / Modern.2bisacsh1 aBeardsworth, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaflak, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagan, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHandwerk, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrell, David Farrell, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlotnitsky, Arkady, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlotnitsky, Arkady, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPlug, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRajan, Tilottama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRajan, Tilottama, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSchulte-Sasse, Jochen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmyth, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWarminski,